# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clickjacking-prevention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Clickjacking is an instance of the confused deputy problem, wherein a computer is tricked into misusing its authority.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In 2002, it had been noted that it was possible to load a transparent layer over a web page and have the user's input affect the transparent layer without the user noticing.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] However, fixes only started to trickle in around 2004, and the general problem was mostly ignored as a major issue until 2008.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In 2008, Jeremiah Grossman and Robert Hansen (of SecTheory) had discovered that Adobe Flash Player was able to be clickjacked, allowing an attacker to gain access to a user's computer without the user's knowledge.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Grossman and Hansen coined the term "clickjacking", a portmanteau of the words "click" and "hijacking".
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] As more attacks of a similar nature were discovered, the focus of the term "UI redressing" was changed to describe the category of these attacks, rather than just clickjacking itself.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] One form of clickjacking takes advantage of vulnerabilities that are present in applications or web pages to allow the attacker to manipulate the user's computer for their own advantage.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] For example, a clickjacked page tricks a user into performing undesired actions by clicking on concealed links.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] On a clickjacked page, the attackers load another page over the original page in a transparent layer to trick the user into taking actions, the outcomes of which will not be the same as the user expects.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The unsuspecting users think that they are clicking visible buttons, while they are actually performing actions on the invisible page, clicking buttons of the page below the layer.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The hidden page may be an authentication page; therefore, the attackers can trick users into performing actions which the users never intended.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] There is no way of tracing such actions to the attackers later, as the users would have been genuinely authenticated on the hidden page.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Classic clickjacking refers to a situation when an attacker uses hidden layers on web pages to manipulate the actions a user's cursor does, resulting in misleading the user about what truly is being clicked on.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] A user might receive an email with a link to a video about a news item, but another webpage, say a product page on Amazon, can be "hidden" on top or underneath the "PLAY" button of the news video.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The user tries to "play" the video but actually "buys" the product from Amazon.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The hacker can only send a single click, so they rely on the fact that the visitor is both logged into Amazon and has 1-click ordering enabled.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] While technical implementation of these attacks may be challenging due to cross-browser incompatibilities, a number of tools such as BeEF or Metasploit Project offer almost fully automated exploitation of clients on vulnerable websites.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Clickjacking may be facilitated by – or may facilitate – other web attacks, such as XSS.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Likejacking is a malicious technique of tricking users viewing a website into "liking" a Facebook page or other social media posts/accounts that they did not intentionally mean to "like".
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The term "likejacking" came from a comment posted by Corey Ballou in the article *How to "Like" Anything on the Web (Safely)*, which is one of the first documented postings explaining the possibility of malicious activity regarding Facebook's "like" button.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] According to an article in *IEEE Spectrum*, a solution to likejacking was developed at one of Facebook's hackathons.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] A "Like" bookmarklet is available that avoids the possibility of likejacking present in the Facebook like button.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Nested clickjacking, compared to classic clickjacking, works by embedding a malicious web frame between two frames of the original, harmless web page: that from the framed page and that which is displayed on the top window.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This works due to a vulnerability in the HTTP header `X-Frame-Options`, in which, when this element has the value `SAMEORIGIN`, the web browser only checks the two aforementioned layers.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The fact that additional frames can be added in between these two while remaining undetected means that attackers can use this for their benefit.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In the past, with Google+ and the faulty version of `X-Frame-Options`, attackers were able to insert frames of their choice by using the vulnerability present in Google's Image Search engine.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In between the image display frames, which were present in Google+ as well, these attacker-controlled frames were able to load and not be restricted, allowing for the attackers to mislead whomever came upon the image display page.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] CursorJacking is a UI redressing technique to change the cursor from the location the user perceives, discovered in 2010 by Eddy Bordi, a researcher at vulnerability.fr.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Marcus Niemietz demonstrated this with a custom cursor icon, and in 2012 Mario Heiderich did so by hiding the cursor.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Jordi Chancel, a researcher at Alternativ-Testing.fr, discovered a CursorJacking vulnerability using Flash, HTML and JavaScript code in Mozilla Firefox on Mac OS X systems (fixed in Firefox 30.0) which can lead to arbitrary code execution and webcam spying.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Different from other clickjacking techniques that redress a UI, MouseJack is a wireless hardware-based UI vulnerability first reported by Marc Newlin of Bastille.net in 2016 which allows external keyboard input to be injected into vulnerable dongles.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Logitech supplied firmware patches but other manufacturers failed to respond to this vulnerability.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In Browserless clickjacking, attackers utilize vulnerabilities in programs to replicate classic clickjacking in them, without being required to use the presence of a web browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This method of clickjacking is mainly prevalent among mobile devices, usually on Android devices, especially due to the way in which toast notifications work.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Because toast notifications have a small delay in between the moment the notification is requested and the moment the notification actually displays on-screen, attackers are capable of using that gap to create a dummy button that lies hidden underneath the notification and can still be clicked on.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] CookieJacking is a form of clickjacking in which cookies are stolen from the victim's web browsers.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This is done by tricking the user into dragging an object which seemingly appears harmless but is in fact making the user select the entire content of the cookie being targeted.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] From there, the attacker can acquire the cookie and all of the data that it possesses.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In fileJacking, attackers use the web browser's capability to navigate through the computer and access computer files in order to acquire personal data.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] It does so by tricking the user into establishing an active file server (through the file and folder selection window that browsers use).
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] With this, attackers can now access and take files from their victims' computers.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Most managers did not protect against iFrame- and redirection-based attacks and exposed additional passwords where password synchronization had been used between multiple devices.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] According to Google's "Browser Security Handbook" from 2008, NoScript's ClearClick is a "freely available product that offers a reasonable degree of protection" against Clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Protection from the newer cursorjacking attack was added to NoScript 2.2.8 RC1.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The "NoClickjack" web browser add-on (browser extension) adds client-side clickjack protection for users of Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera and Microsoft Edge without interfering with the operation of legitimate iFrames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] NoClickjack is based on technology developed for GuardedID.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The NoClickjack add-on is free of charge.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] GuardedID (a commercial product) includes client-side clickjack protection for users of Internet Explorer without interfering with the operation of legitimate iFrames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] GuardedID clickjack protection forces all frames to become visible.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] GuardedID teams with the add-on NoClickjack to add protection for Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera and Microsoft Edge.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Gazelle is a Microsoft Research project secure web browser based on IE, that uses an OS-like security model and has its own limited defenses against clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In Gazelle, a window of different origin may only draw dynamic content over another window's screen space if the content it draws is opaque.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The Intersection Observer v2 API introduces the concept of tracking the actual "visibility" of a target element as a human being would define it.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This allows a framed widget to detect when it's being covered.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The feature is enabled by default since Google Chrome 74, released in April 2019.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The API is also implemented by other Chromium-based browsers, such as Microsoft Edge and Opera.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Web site owners can protect their users against UI redressing (frame based clickjacking) on the server side by including a framekiller JavaScript snippet in those pages they do not want to be included inside frames from different sources.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Such JavaScript-based protection is not always reliable.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This is especially true on Internet Explorer, where this kind of countermeasure can be circumvented "by design" by including the targeted page inside an `<IFRAME SECURITY=restricted>` element.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] Introduced in 2009 in Internet Explorer 8 was a new HTTP header `X-Frame-Options` which offered a partial protection against clickjacking and was adopted by other browsers (Safari, Firefox, Chrome, and Opera) shortly afterwards.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The header, when set by website owner, declares its preferred framing policy: values of `DENY`, `ALLOW-FROM *origin*`, or `SAMEORIGIN` will prevent any framing, framing by external sites, or allow framing only by the specified site, respectively.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In addition to that, some advertising sites return a non-standard `ALLOWALL` value with the intention to allow framing their content on any page (equivalent of not setting X-Frame-Options at all).
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] In 2013 the X-Frame-Options header has been officially published as RFC 7034, but is not an Internet standard.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The document is provided for informational purposes only.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The W3C's Content Security Policy Level 2 Recommendation provides an alternative security directive, frame-ancestors, which is intended to obsolete the X-Frame-Options header.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] A security header like X-Frame-Options will not protect users against clickjacking attacks that are not using a frame.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] The `frame-ancestors` directive of Content Security Policy (introduced in version 1.1) can allow or disallow embedding of content by potentially hostile pages using iframe, object, etc.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] This directive obsoletes the X-Frame-Options directive.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/clickjacking] If a page is served with both headers, the frame-ancestors policy should be preferred by the browser, although this requirement was ignored by older versions of some browsers.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] A **framekiller** (or **framebuster** or **framebreaker**) is a technique used by websites and web applications to prevent their web pages from being displayed within an HTML frame element.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] A frame is a subdivision of a Web browser window and can act like a smaller window.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] A framekiller is usually used to prevent a website from being loaded from within a frameset without permission, which might be part of an attack, as with clickjacking.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] Framekiller scripts have largely been replaced by the usage of `X-Frame-Options` and `Content-Security-Policy` headers, which prevent the page from being loaded in a frame in the first place.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] These headers are supported by all modern browsers and do not require the use of JavaScript.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] These headers are also intended to be specified inside the web server software, rather than directly inside the HTML.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] Framekillers are implemented using JavaScript that validates if the current window is the main window.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] This approach was proposed in 2010 by Gustav Rydstedt, Elie Bursztein, Dan Boneh and Collin Jackson in a paper that highlighted the limitations of existing frame-busting techniques along with techniques allowing to bypass them.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] An alternative choice is to allow the user to determine whether to let the framekiller work.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] The logic here was to display the page, but check if the top location is the same as the current page, and replace the top by current if not.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] This method however can be easily bypassed by blocking execution of the framebuster script from the outer frame.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] Client-side JavaScript solution relies on the end-user's browser enforcing their own security.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] This makes it a beneficial, but unreliable, means of disallowing your page to be embedded in other pages.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] The iframe in HTML5 has a sandbox attribute.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] The attribute's value is a set of allowed capabilities for the iframe's content.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] If the value is empty or not set, the iframe's content will not execute JavaScript, and won't allow top-level navigation.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framekiller] By specifying allow-scripts in the space separated set of exceptions in the value, the iframe will allow JavaScript, but will still disallow top-level navigation, rendering framekillers in the iframe impotent.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] In the context of a web browser, a **frame** is a part of a web page or browser window which displays content independent of its container, with the ability to load content independently.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The HTML or media elements in a frame may come from a web site distinct from the site providing the enclosing content.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] This practice, known as **framing**, is today often regarded as a violation of same-origin policy.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] In HTML, a **frameset** is a group of named frames to which web pages and media can be directed; an **iframe** provides for a frame to be placed inside the body of a document.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Since the early 2000s, concern for usability and accessibility has motivated diminished use of framesets and the HTML5 standard does not support them.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The frames in HTML are created using the `<frameset></frameset>` tag pair.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The `<frameset>` tag is a container tag for all other tags that are used to create frames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The `<frameset>` tag replaces the `<body>` tag in frameset documents.The `<frameset>` tag defines how to divide the window into frames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Each frameset defines a set of rows or columns.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] If user define frames by using the `rows` attribute then horizontal frames are created.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] If user define frames by using `cols` then vertical frames are created.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] If set to an integer greater than 0, the user can resize the frames by dragging this border, unless a `noresize` attribute is present in a frame element.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] If border is set to 0, no border will be displayed and content in different frames will abut each other without delineation.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The `iframe` element is used inline within a normal HTML body, and defines the initial content and name similarly to the `frame` element.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Any text inside an `<iframe></iframe>` tag pair will be displayed in browsers that do not understand the iframe tag.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Netscape Navigator 2.0 introduced the elements used for frames in March 1996.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Other browser vendors such as Apple with Cyberdog followed later that year.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] At that time, Netscape proposed frames to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) for inclusion in the HTML 3.0 standard.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Frames were used to display and navigate early online magazines and web apps, such as webmail services and web chat sites.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Frames had the advantage of allowing elements to be displayed sitewide without requiring server features such as server-side includes or CGI support.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] These features were not common on early web servers accessible to the public.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Early websites often used a frame at the top to display a banner which could not be scrolled away.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] These banner frames sometimes included the site's logo as well as advertising.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] XHTML 1.1, the intended successor to HTML 4, removed all frames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] XFrames, the intended eventual replacement, provided the composite URI to address a populated frameset.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The later HTML5 standard removed framesets by means differing from XHTML.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The `iframe` element remains with a number of "sandboxing" options intended for sharing content between sites.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] The practice of framing HTML content led to numerous criticisms, most centering on usability and accessibility concerns.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] Frames create both technical and user-interface difficulties for enforcement of the same-origin policy.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] As an example of the latter, an outer page can trick a user into performing an action on an inner page (loaded using the iframe element) which has been made 99% transparent.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/framing-world-wide-web] As web technology developed, many of the purposes for which frames were used became possible in ways that avoided the problems identified with frames.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A **web browser**, often abbreviated as **browser**, is an application for accessing websites.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] When a user requests a web page from a particular website, the browser retrieves its files from a web server and then displays the page on the user's screen.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Browsers can also display content stored locally on the user's device.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Browsers are used on a range of devices, including desktops, laptops, tablets, smartphones, smartwatches, smart televisions and consoles.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] As of 2026, the most used browsers worldwide are Google Chrome (~69% market share), Safari (~16%), Edge (~5%), Firefox (~2%), Samsung Browser (~2%), and Opera (~2%).
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] As of 2023, an estimated 5.4 billion people had used a browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The purpose of a web browser is to fetch content and display it on the user's device.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] This process begins when the user inputs a Uniform Resource Locator (URL), such as *`https://en.wikipedia.org/`*, into the browser's address bar.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Virtually all URLs on the Web start with either *`http:`* or *`https:`* which means they are retrieved with the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] For secure mode (HTTPS), the connection between the browser and web server is encrypted, providing a secure and private data transfer.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] For this reason, a web browser is often referred to as an HTTP client or a user agent.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Requisite materials, including text, style sheets, images, and other types of multimedia, are downloaded from the server.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Once the materials have been downloaded, the web browser's engine (also known as a layout engine or rendering engine) is responsible for converting those resources into an interactive visual representation of the page on the user's device.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Modern web browsers also contain separate JavaScript engines which enable more complex interactive applications inside the browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A web browser that does not render a graphical user interface is known as a headless browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Web pages usually contain hyperlinks to other pages and resources.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Each link contains a URL, and when it is clicked or tapped, the browser navigates to the new resource.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Most browsers use an internal cache of web page resources to improve loading times for subsequent visits to the same page.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The cache can store many items, such as large images, so they do not need to be downloaded from the server again.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Cached items are usually only stored for as long as the web server stipulates in its HTTP response messages.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A web browser is not the same thing as a search engine, though the two are often confused.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A search engine is a website that provides links to other websites and allows users to search for specific resources using a textual query.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] However, web browsers are often used to access search engines, and most modern browsers allow users to access a default search engine directly by typing a query into the address bar.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The first web browser, called WorldWideWeb, was created in 1990 by Sir Tim Berners-Lee.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] He then recruited Nicola Pellow to write the Line Mode Browser, which displayed web pages on dumb terminals.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The Mosaic web browser was released in April 1993, and was later credited as the first web browser to find mainstream popularity.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Its innovative graphical user interface made the World Wide Web easy to navigate and thus more accessible to the average person.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] This, in turn, sparked the Internet boom of the 1990s, when the Web grew at a very rapid rate.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released the Mosaic-influenced Netscape Navigator in 1994.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Navigator quickly became the most popular browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Within a few years, Microsoft gained a dominant position in the browser market for two reasons: it bundled Internet Explorer with its popular Windows operating system and did so as freeware with no restrictions on usage.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The market share of Internet Explorer peaked at over 95% in the early 2000s.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] In 1998, Netscape launched what would become the Mozilla Foundation to create a new browser using the open-source software model.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] This work evolved into the Firefox browser, first released by Mozilla in 2004.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Firefox's market share peaked at 32% in 2010.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Apple released its Safari browser in 2003; it remains the dominant browser on Apple devices, though it did not become popular elsewhere.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, which steadily took market share from Internet Explorer and became the most popular browser in 2012.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Chrome has remained dominant ever since.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] In 2015, Microsoft replaced Internet Explorer with Edge [Legacy] for the Windows 10 release.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] In 2020, this legacy version was replaced by a new Chromium-based version of Edge.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Since the early 2000s, browsers have greatly expanded their HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and multimedia capabilities.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] One reason has been to enable more sophisticated websites, such as web apps.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Another factor is the significant increase of broadband connectivity in many parts of the world, enabling people to access data-intensive content, such as streaming HD video on YouTube, that was not possible during the era of dial-up modems.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Starting in the mid-2020s, browsers with integrated artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities, known as AI browsers, have become increasingly common.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] This includes both new entrants to the browser market, such as Perplexity Comet and ChatGPT Atlas, and established browsers that added AI features, such as Chrome with the Gemini chatbot and Edge with the Copilot chatbot.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The most popular browsers share many features.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] They automatically log users' browsing history, unless the users turn off their browsing history or use the non-logging private mode.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] They also allow users to set bookmarks, customize the browser with extensions, and manage their downloads and passwords.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Some provide a sync service and web accessibility features.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] While mobile browsers have similar UI features as desktop versions, the limitations of the often-smaller touch screens require mobile UIs to be simpler.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The difference is significant for users accustomed to keyboard shortcuts.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Responsive web design is used to create websites that offer a consistent experience across the desktop and mobile versions of the website and across varying screen sizes.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The most popular desktop browsers also have sophisticated web development tools.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Access to some web content — particularly streaming services like Netflix, Disney+, and Spotify — is restricted by Digital Rights Management (DRM) software.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A web browser is able to access DRM-restricted content through the use of a Content Decryption Module (CDM) such as Widevine.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] As of 2020, the CDMs used by dominant web browsers require browser providers to pay costly license fees, making it unfeasible for most independent open-source browsers to offer access to DRM-restricted content.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Google Chrome has been the dominant browser worldwide since the mid-2010s and currently has a 69% global market share on all devices.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] The other two browsers in the top four are made from different codebases.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Safari, based on Apple's WebKit code, is the second most popular web browser and is dominant on Apple devices, resulting in a 16% global share.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Firefox, in fourth place, with about 2% market share, is based on Mozilla's code.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Both of these codebases are open-source, so a number of small niche browsers are also made from them.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Prior to late 2016, the majority of web traffic came from desktop computers.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] However, since then, mobile devices (smartphones) have represented the majority of web traffic.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] As of February 2025, mobile devices represent a 62% share of Internet traffic, followed by desktop at 36% and tablet at 2%.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Web browsers are popular targets for hackers, who exploit security holes to steal information, destroy files, and partake in other malicious activities.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Browser vendors regularly patch these security holes, so users are strongly encouraged to keep their browser software updated.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Other protection measures are antivirus software and being aware of scams.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] During the course of browsing, cookies received from various websites are stored by the browser.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Some of them contain login credentials or site preferences.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] However, others are used for tracking user behavior over long periods of time, so browsers typically provide a section in the menu for deleting cookies.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Some browsers have more proactive protection against cookies and trackers that limit their functionality and ability to track user behaviour.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Finer-grained management of cookies usually requires a browser extension.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Telemetry data is collected by most popular web browsers, which can usually be opted out of by the user.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] A study from 2020 portrays that there are two tiers of browsers in terms of privacy: the privacy-focused ones (Brave, DuckDuckGo, LibreWolf, Tor,Mullvad, Helium and Firefox-Focus) perform better than popular ones (Chrome, Firefox, and Safari) and recommend the first ones.
[src:clickjacking-prevention/web-browser] Blocking fingerprinting, cookies, tracking scripts, ads, etc. seems to explain that difference.
